      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies, I sometimes get a bit too... *enthusiastic* when discussing statistical anomalies! I meant that influential points are like tiny, mischievous data-scrambling goblins that have a disproportionate amount of power over your regression line. They don't just sit there; they actively *pull* the entire trend in a direction that doesn't represent the majority of your data. They are the statistical equivalent of a small, noisy group of hobgoblins throwing rocks at the main caravan.\n\nTo be perfectly clear, Cook's Distance identifies observations that have a high influence on the model fit. If a point has a high Cook's Distance, removing it might significantly change your slope or intercept, indicating it's not behaving like the rest of the data. You should examine those specific points—perhaps they represent a unique housing situation, like a mansion built on a swamp, which is just too different from the average.",
